  "description": "</p> <p>Acaena microphylla is a prostrate branching herb perennial which forms a 1m dense carpet of green to bronze-green leaves with a height of 3 cm. The leaves are up to 3cm in length.<br>In December to March when in bloom, the bright red coloured, burr-like flower-heads (2.3cm in diameter) form bright red patches which can last until April.<br>Found in the wild in grasslands, riverbeds and herb fields of the Volcanic Plateau in the Tongariro National Park up to 1,100m altitude.<br><br>The Royal Horticultural Society has given Acaena microphylla their prestigious Award of Garden Merit which is for plants of outstanding excellence. It can be purchased from specialised nurseries.<br><br>Photographed at Otari Wilton Bush Reserve.<br>Photo showing bronze-green leaves.and burr-like flower-heads. Photo taken March after long dry summer<br><a href=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0005/2049/Acaena_microphylla__Scarlet_Bidibid_-002.JPG\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0005/2049/Acaena_microphylla__Scarlet_Bidibid_-002.JPG\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"auto\"></a> <br><br>A close of a burr-like flower-head. (March.)<br><img src=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0005/2044/Acaena_microphylla__Scarlet_Bidibid_-001.JPG\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"auto\"> <br><br>The developed burr with hooks.<a style=\"font-size: 1em; line-height: 1em;\" href=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0003/1649/Acaena_microphylla__Scarlet_bidibid-002.JPG\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0003/1649/Acaena_microphylla__Scarlet_bidibid-002.JPG\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"auto\"></a></p> <p><a style=\"font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em;\" href=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0003/1669/Acaena_microphylla__Scarlet_bidibid-005.JPG\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0003/1669/Acaena_microphylla__Scarlet_bidibid-005.JPG\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"auto\"></a> <br><br>A developing flower head (November)<a style=\"font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em;\" href=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0004/4814/Acaena_microphylla__scarlet_bidibid-006.JPG\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0004/4814/Acaena_microphylla__scarlet_bidibid-006.JPG\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"auto\"></a></p> <p><img src=\"http://ketenewplymouth.peoplesnetworknz.info/image_files/0000/0003/1634/Acaena_microphylla__Scarlet_bidibid-001.JPG\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"auto\"> <br><br>Thanks to Wikipedia for text and information: <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/%20\" target=\"_blank\">https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/ </a></p> <br style=\"clear:both;\"> <div class=\"hr\"> </div> ",
